IMDB Exploratory Analysis Tutorial¶

Jason He 113590306 Shihang Zeng 115048621

IMDb is the one of the biggest movies rating website in the world, we would like to analyze the correlation between rating score and all the other elements, and find out what element can affect the rating score of a movie.

Also we want to build a model to predict the rating scroe of a movie based on the data we have on IMDb, so that we can understand how to make a movie that people think is good, and what kind of movie the investor and movie maker should make.

One of the application we can use for this project is that we can build a better movie suggestion machine learning algorithm for companies like Nextflix.

Getting Started¶

Before getting started, you will need to install the various libraries that we will use. We will be using many commonly-used libraries such as Pandas and Numpy, as well as Matplotlib and Ggplot for plotting data and Statsmodels for linear regression models and features. All of these canbe installed using pip:

% pip install

This tutorial will use data from Imdb pulled from Kaggle.com. The database is accessed through URL in this tutorial, but the database can also, be The database can also be downloaded into the folder of this notebook to be accessed locally on your machine through https://www.kaggle.com/orgesleka/imdbmovies.

Univariate Analysis¶

We will be analysis the entirety of the database without categorially grouping for genres, starting with univariate analysis of relevant variables of interest. We will do this with simple histograms of 'imdbRating', 'year', 'duration', 'ratingCount', and 'nrOfUserReviews'.

In [8]:
imdb['imdbRating'].plot.hist(alpha=1, bins=20)
Out[8]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2f1dc50>

The 'imdbRating' distribution looks nearly normal, without a small skewness towards the lower ratings. The median rating looks to be about a 7.0.

In [9]:
imdb['year'].plot.hist(alpha=1, bins=25)
Out[9]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x146fe030>

The 'year' distribution shows a steady increase in movie production over the years until when it exploded, beginning around the 1980s, dramatically increasing since then.

In [10]:
imdb['duration'].plot.hist(alpha=1, bins=100)
Out[10]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x143815d0>

The 'duration' distribution is fairly normal, with a balanced central tendency and a median of around 7000 seconds. The only inconsistency in a supposed normal distribution is the small pocket of sub-2000-second-long movies. This is likely due to a collection of short films in the database.

In [11]:
imdb['ratingCount'].plot.hist(alpha=1, bins=50)
Out[11]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x146a9250>

The 'ratingCount' distribution shows an exponential-logarithmic distribution. Most movies in the database have under 20,000 ratings.

In [12]:
imdb['nrOfUserReviews'].plot.hist(alpha=1, bins=50)
Out[12]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x14c692b0>

The 'nrOfUserReviews' distribution also shows an exponential-logarithmic distribution. Most movies in the database have under 100 reviews. This also suggests that 'ratingCount' and 'nrOfUserReviews' could be closely related.

We will further intestigate the distribution for 'ratingCount' and 'nrOfUserReviews with describe().

Bivariate Analysis¶

We will now perform bivariate analysis for the data. We'll train a linear regression model with Statsmodels for each variable of interest against 'imdbRating' with the hopes of uncovering what effect these variables have on 'imdbRating'.

In [15]:
reg = smf.ols(formula='imdbRating ~ year', data=imdb).fit()
b,m = reg.params
x = imdb['year']
imdb.plot.scatter(x='year',y='imdbRating',s=.02)
plt.plot(x,m*x + b,'-',color='y')
Out[15]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x14e6bb90>]

The scatterplot shows that 'year' has a negative correlation with 'imdbRating'. This means that ratings will be increasingly harsher as the years go on. The opaqueness of the right side of the scatterplot shows a large majority of movies are younger. This corresponds with what we've seen from the histogram for 'year'.

We will now just summary() to on our trained regression model to reveal more information about the distribution. This analysis procedure will be used for all variables of interest.

The scatter plot shows that 'duration' has a positive correlation with 'imdbRating'. However, even with a scalar as low as 0.02, you can see that distribution of points is still very dense and opaque. This reveals that a vast majority of movies have very similar durations. The nonoutlier grouping of points on the left of the plot is likely due to the data from short films, which we have also seen in the histogram for 'duration'.

The regression model without the 'nrOfUserReviews' variable has an R-squared value of .132, while the regression model with the variable as an R-squared value of .149. This suggests that it would be better to include the variable in our final regression model.

Based on the coefficients in the summary, our final regression model would be:

imdbRating = -0.0127 year + 0.0001 duration + 0.000005106 ratingCount - 0.0005 nrOfUserReviews + 31.1787

While the R-squared for this model is still quite low, it is the best that we can do with the data that we have available for us.

# combine the catagory data into one column 

imdb['Cata'] = ""
for i , row in imdb.iterrows():
    if(row['War']==1):
        if(row['Cata']==""):
            imdb.set_value(i,'Cata',"war")
        else:   
            row['Cata'] = "war"
            imdb = imdb.append(row)
    if(row['Drama']==1):
        if(len(imdb['Cata'][i])==0):
            imdb.set_value(i,'Cata',"drama")
        else:   
            row['Cata'] = "drama"
            imdb = imdb.append(row)
    if(row['Animation']==1):
        if(len(imdb['Cata'][i])==0):
            imdb.set_value(i,'Cata',"animation")
        else:   
            row['Cata'] = "animation"
            imdb = imdb.append(row)
    if(row['Romance']==1):
        if(len(imdb['Cata'][i])==0):
            imdb.set_value(i,'Cata',"romance")
        else:
            row['Cata'] = "romance"
            imdb = imdb.append(row)
    if(row['Crime']==1):

Based on all the analysis above, we believe that we can use our genral linear regression model to predict the range the rating of the movie in the category of drama, romance and crime. All the other catagories are bit different then our linear regression model.

The linear regression of the data from war has greater slope than the other. The linear regression of the data from comedy has a smaller slope and y-intercept.
